Session 1: Prior, likelihood and prior predictive distributions

1 Statistical model

A statistical model , \(M\), is a set of probability models indexed by a parameter that is known to belong to a parameter space \(\Omega\).

\[M = \{P(y | \theta), \theta \in \Omega\}.\]

When we do inference, we assume that data \(Y = y\) is coming from a probability model \(P(y| \theta^{*})\) that is known to belong to \(M\). We assume that \(\theta^{*} \in \Omega\).

\[Y | \theta \sim P(y| \theta)\]

Example:

Which would be the statistical model in:

  • Tossing a coin 20 times, how many tails?
  • Choose 20 random places in the world and see how many times it is land (or sea)?

\[M = \{Binomial(n = 20, \theta), \theta \in [0,1]\}\]

                args = list(size = 20, prob = 0.5),
                geom = "bar") +
  xlim(c(0, 20))

# b) Sampling
sample <- rbinom(p=0.5, size=20, n=10000)
ggplot(tibble(sample))+
  geom_bar(aes(sample), fill="cyan",width = 0.2)

# c) Tibble
sample <- tibble(
  x = 0:20,
  y = dbinom(x, 20, 0.5)
)
ggplot(sample) +
  geom_bar(aes(x, y), stat = "identity")

2 Prior distribution: \(\Pi(\theta)\)

A bayesian also starts with a statistical model:

\(M = \{P(y | \theta), \theta \in \Omega\}\).
  • Consider \(\theta\) as a random variable
  • Choose a distribution on \(\Omega\) for \(\theta\) that captures your information about \(\theta\) before observing data
  • \(\Pi(\theta)\) is the prior distribution

If \(V(\theta)\) is large \(\Leftrightarrow\) \(\Pi(\theta)\) less informative
If \(V(\theta)\) is small \(\Leftrightarrow\) \(\Pi(\theta)\) is very informative

3 Bayesian Model: \(M + \Pi(\theta)\)

Bayesian model : list of probability models, \({P(y|\theta), \theta \in \Omega}\) ranked from more credible to least credible based on the values taken by \(\Pi(\theta)\).

3.1 Beta distribution

A family of distributions that are suported on [0,1] that are convenient are \(Beta(\alpha, \beta)\) disribution. \(0< \alpha, \beta < \infty\)

\(\alpha>1, \beta>1\): Shape \(\cap\)
\(\alpha>1, \beta<1\): Shape /
\(\alpha<1, \beta>1\): Shape \
\(\alpha<1, \beta<1\): Shape V

Interpretation:

\(Beta(\alpha, \beta)\): what you know is equivalent to tossing a coin \(n=\alpha + \beta\) times and observing \(\alpha\) heads and \(\beta\) tails.

\[E(\theta) = \frac{\alpha}{\alpha + \beta}\]
\[V(\theta)=\frac{\alpha \cdot \beta}{(\alpha + \beta)^2 (\alpha + \beta +1)}\]

4 Likelihood function

Before data, if we fix \(\theta\), the statistical model \(M=\{P(y|\theta), \theta \in \Omega\}\) becomes a probabilistic model (a function of \(y\)).

Once you have data \(Y=y\) you can switch things around. Then \(P(y| \theta)\) is a function of \(\theta\). This is the likelihood function : \(\ell_{Y=y}(\theta) \propto p(y | \theta)\)

Example:

  • Suppose we throw the coin 20 times and get 12 tails

\[l_y(\theta) \propto {20 \choose 12} \theta^{12} (1- \theta)^{20-12}\]

The likelihood function orders the values in \(\Omega\) from the more likely to the least likely.

Prior - likelihood: the difference is that you have a prior \(\Pi(\theta)\) without the need of data. You can not have a likelihood function without data.

Exercise:

Plot the previous likelihood function

# dbinom(x, size, prob, log = FALSE)

  omega = seq(0, 1, 0.01), 
  likelihood = dbinom(12, 20, omega)) 

ggplot(df) +
  geom_line(aes(omega, likelihood))

5 Prior predictive distribution: \(P_{\Pi} (\tilde y)\)

What do you do if you care about future values of \(y\), \(\tilde y\)?

What do we know about \(\tilde y\) before answering the data?

\(\left\{\begin{matrix} M = \{p(\tilde y | \theta), \theta \in \Omega\} \\ \pi(\theta) \end{matrix}\right.\)

If you assume this, what is your best bet as a distribution of \(\tilde y\)?

\(P_{\pi}(\tilde y) = \int_{\Omega}{p(\tilde y | \theta)\pi(\theta) d\theta} = E_{\pi}(p(\tilde y | \theta))\) is the prior predictive distribution .

\(p(\tilde y | \theta)\) is the weighted average of \(p(y | \theta)\)

This is what you will use if you want to predict \(\tilde y\) without data.

Exercise:

\[Y|p \sim Binomial(n=20, p)\] \[p \sim Beta(a=200, b=200)\]

  • Simulate 10000 draws from prior density: p_sim
  • Simulate 10000 draws from the predictive density: y_sim
  • Plot the prior predictive density
  • Compute the probability of obtaining less than 5 tails
  • Find a 90 percent prediction interval for the number of tails
## Predictive simulation

# Simulate 10000 draws from prior density: p_sim
p_sim <- rbeta(10000, 200, 200)
ggplot(tibble(p_sim)) +
  geom_density(aes(p_sim))

# Simulate 10000 draws from the predictive density: y_sim
y_sim <- rbinom(1000, 20, p_sim)

# Plot the prior predictive density
ggplot(tibble(y_sim)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y_sim))

# Compute the probability of less than 5 tails
mean(y_sim < 5)
[1] 0.008
# Find a 90 percent prediction interval for the number of tails
quantile(y_sim, c(0.05, 0.95))
   5%   95% 
 6.00 13.05
